 Identity Inclusive Sexual Assault Myth Scale (IISAMS) to explore the unique aspects of sexual assault and the process of disclosure as experienced by queer victims. They also incorporate participant recommendations, collected during interviews, as they foreground ways for more effectively preventing and responding to sexual violence throughout contemporary society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aGender identity. 0aSexual abuse victims. 0aSexual minoritiesxViolence against. 0aSexual minorities-Violence against. 0aSexual orientation. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sexual Abuse & Harassment.2bisacsh1 aBryan, Valerie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKoon-Magnin, Sarah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPope, Amber, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertLynne Rienner Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311078354440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978162637793640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781626377936423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781626377936/original  a978-3-11-078354-4  Lynne Rienner Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK